        <name>16.5.4.1 The Taylor series</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;h3&gt;&lt;span&gt;The Taylor series&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Taylor series&lt;/strong&gt; is a generalisation of the Maclaurin series being a power series developed in powers of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\((x-x_0)\)&lt;/span&gt; rather than in powers of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(x\)&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="HELM_keypoint"&gt;
    &lt;h4&gt;Key Point&lt;/h4&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;If the function &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(f(x)\)&lt;/span&gt; can be differentiated as often as required at &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(x=x_0\)&lt;/span&gt; then: &lt;span class="math display"&gt;\[f(x)=f(x_0)+(x-x_0)f'(x_0)+\dfrac{(x-x_0)^2}{2!}f''(x_0)+\cdots\]&lt;/span&gt;        This is called the Taylor series of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(f(x)\)&lt;/span&gt; about the point &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(x_0\)&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Maclaurin expansion is the Taylor expansion obtained if &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(x_0\)&lt;/span&gt; is chosen to be zero.&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
